{"title_page": "Linx (band)", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Linx\n| image               =\n| caption             = \n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               = \n| origin              = [[United Kingdom]]\n| genre               = {{flat list|\n*[[Brit funk]]\n*[[Soul music|soul]]\n}}\n| years_active        = 1980\u20131983\n| instrument          = \n| label               = [[Chrysalis Records]]\n| past_members        = [[David Grant (singer)|David Grant]]<br/>[[Junior Giscombe]]<br/>Bob Carter<br/>Andy Duncan<br/>Canute Edwards<br/>Peter Martin\n}}\n'''Linx''' were a [[British soul]]/[[Brit funk]] [[band (music)|band]] consisting of [[David Grant (singer)|David Grant]] ([[lead vocal]]s), Bob Carter ([[keyboard instrument|keyboards]]), Andy Duncan ([[drum]]s), Canute Edwards ([[guitar]]), Peter Martin ([[bass guitar|bass]]) (aka Sketch) and [[Junior Giscombe]] (backing vocals). Bob Carter and Andy Duncan were [[session musician]]s who were known for their contribution to [[Hazel O'Connor]]'s ''[[Breaking Glass]]'' album and movie.\n\nAfter their first hit in 1980, the band slimmed down to a duo of Grant and Martin.<ref name=\"carrieanddavidgrant.co.uk\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.carrieanddavidgrant.co.uk/biography.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081031223006/http://www.carrieanddavidgrant.co.uk/biography.html|url-status=dead|title=Biography|website=Carrieanddavidgrant.co.uk|archivedate=October 31, 2008}}</ref> Peter Martin (the bassist) joined the band [[23 Skidoo (band)|23 Skidoo]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://instrumentfind.com/|title=Instrument Find|website=Instrumentfind.com}}</ref> Junior Giscombe became a pop singer in his own right.\n\n==Overview==\nLinx had six entries on the [[UK Singles Chart]] from mid-1980 until mid-1982. The band's biggest success was \"Intuition,\" which reached number 7 in early 1981. <ref name=\"C\" /> Other hits included \"You're Lying\" and \"So This is Romance.\" Linx also contributed the track \"Don't Get in My Way\" to the influential [[C81 (album)|C81]] compilation cassette released by ''[[New Musical Express]]'' magazine in 1981.\n\nLinx's success with \"Intuition\" was assisted by a BBC technician's strike, which resulted in only music videos and repeat performances being allowed to be used on ''[[Top Of The Pops]]'' for a period. This led to the video for \"Intuition\", first played when the song was in the 60's in the music charts, being shown several times. This helped the single reach the Top Ten.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}    \n\nLinx split in early 1983. Grant went on to have a number of [[solo (music)|solo]] hits.<ref name=\"carrieanddavidgrant.co.uk\"/> More recently, he was featured as a vocal coach on the [[BBC TV]] show ''[[Fame Academy]].''\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Release date\n! Title      \n! [[UK Albums|UK]]<ref name=\"C\"/>\n! [[Billboard 200|US]]<ref name=\"Billboard 200\">{{cite web |url= https://www.billboard.com/music/linx/chart-history/billboard-200|title=Billboard 200 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=11 July 1981 |website=Billboard.com|access-date=20 Dec 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n! [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums|US R&B Albums]]<ref name='Billboard R&B Albums'>{{cite web |url= http://www.metacritic.com/feature/now-streaming-on-netflix|title=Billboard Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=20 June 1981 |website=Metacritic.com|access-date=20 Dec 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n! Certifications\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1981\n| ''[[Intuition (Linx album)|Intuition]]''\n| <center>8</center>\n|<center>175</center>\n|<center>39</center>\n|* [[British Phonographic Industry|BPI]]: [[Music recording certification|Silver]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bpi.co.uk/award/3374-1951-2|title=Linx: Intuition (Album)|publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry|BPI]]|website=bpi.co.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Go Ahead''\n| <center>35</center>\n|<center>-</center>\n|<center>-</center>\n|\n|}\n\n=== Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Release date\n! Title\n|[[UK Singles|UK]]<ref name=\"C\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/1526/linx/|title=Linx|publisher=[[Official Charts]]|website=officialcharts.com}}</ref>\n! [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|US R&B]]<ref name=\"Billboard R&B Charts\">{{cite web |url= https://www.billboard.com/music/linx/chart-history/r-b-hip-hop-songs|title=Hot R&B/Hip Hop Songs |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=1981 |website=Billboard.com|access-date=20 Dec 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n![[Dance Club Songs|US Dance]]<ref name=\"Billboard Dance Charts\">{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/linx/chart-history/dance-club-play-songs |title=Dance Club Charts |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=11 April 1981 |website=Billboard.com|access-date=20 Dec 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n! Certifications\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1980\n| \"Rise And Shine\"\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n|\n|-\n| \"You're Lying\"\n| <center>15</center>\n| <center>27</center>\n| <center>71</center>\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\"|1981\n| \"Intuition\"\n| <center>7</center>\n|<center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n|* [[British Phonographic Industry|BPI]]: [[Music recording certification|Silver]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bpi.co.uk/award/3374-1951-1|title=Linx: Intuition (Single)|publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry|BPI]]|website=bpi.co.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n| \"Together We Can Shine\"\n| <center>-</center>\n|<center>45</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n|\n|-\n| \"Throw Away the Key\"\n| <center>21</center>\n|<center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n|\n|-\n| \"So This is Romance\"\n| <center>15</center>\n|<center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n|\n|-\n| \"Can't Help Myself\"\n| <center>55</center>\n|<center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1982\n| \"Plaything\"\n| <center>48</center>\n|<center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n|\n|-\n| \"Don't Hit Me With Love\"\n| <center>-</center>\n|<center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n|\n|}\n\n===Compilations===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Release date\n!       Album title      \n|-\n| 1993\n| ''David Grant & Linx - The Best Of David Grant & Linx''\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''The Best Of Linx''\n|}\n<ref>[https://www.discogs.com/artist/56746-Linx Album and Singles Discography]. ''Discogs.com''. Retrieved 29 February 2020</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Linx (band)}}\n[[Category:British funk musical groups]]\n[[Category:British soul musical groups]]\n[[Category:British rhythm and blues musical groups]]\n[[Category:Chrysalis Records artists]]\n\n\n{{UK-band-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Linx\n| image               =\n| caption             = \n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               = \n| origin              = [[United Kingdom]]\n| genre               = {{flat list|\n*[[Brit funk]]\n*[[Soul music|soul]]\n}}\n| years_active        = 1980\u20131983\n| instrument          = \n| label               = [[Chrysalis Records]]\n| past_members        = [[David Grant (singer)|David Grant]]<br/>[[Junior Giscombe]]<br/>Bob Carter<br/>Andy Duncan<br/>Canute Edwards<br/>Peter Martin\n}}\n'''Linx''' were a [[British soul]]/[[Brit funk]] [[band (music)|band]] consisting of [[David Grant (singer)|David Grant]] ([[lead vocal]]s), Bob Carter ([[keyboard instrument|keyboards]]), Andy Duncan ([[drum]]s), Canute Edwards ([[guitar]]), Peter Martin ([[bass guitar|bass]]) (aka Sketch) and [[Junior Giscombe]] (backing vocals). Bob Carter and Andy Duncan were [[session musician]]s who were known for their contribution to [[Hazel O'Connor]]'s ''[[Breaking Glass]]'' album and movie.\n\nAfter their first hit in 1980, the band slimmed down to a duo of Grant and Martin.<ref name=\"carrieanddavidgrant.co.uk\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.carrieanddavidgrant.co.uk/biography.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081031223006/http://www.carrieanddavidgrant.co.uk/biography.html|url-status=dead|title=Biography|website=Carrieanddavidgrant.co.uk|archivedate=October 31, 2008}}</ref> Peter Martin (the bassist) joined the band [[23 Skidoo (band)|23 Skidoo]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://instrumentfind.com/|title=Instrument Find|website=Instrumentfind.com}}</ref> Junior Giscombe became a pop singer in his own right.\n\n==Overview==\nLinx had six entries on the [[UK Singles Chart]] from mid-1980 until mid-1982. The band's biggest success was \"Intuition,\" which reached number 7 in early 1981. <ref name=\"C\" /> Other hits included \"You're Lying\" and \"So This is Romance.\" Linx also contributed the track \"Don't Get in My Way\" to the influential [[C81 (album)|C81]] compilation cassette released by ''[[New Musical Express]]'' magazine in 1981.\n\nLinx's success with \"Intuition\" was assisted by a BBC technician's strike, which resulted in only music videos and repeat performances being allowed to be used on ''[[Top Of The Pops]]'' for a period. This led to the video for \"Intuition\", first played when the song was in the 60's in the music charts, being shown several times. This helped the single reach the Top Ten.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}    \n\nLinx split in early 1983. Grant went on to have a number of [[solo (music)|solo]] hits.<ref name=\"carrieanddavidgrant.co.uk\"/> More recently, he was featured as a vocal coach on the [[BBC TV]] show ''[[Fame Academy]].''\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Release date\n! Title      \n! [[UK Albums|UK]]<ref name=\"C\"/>\n! [[Billboard 200|US]]<ref name=\"Billboard 200\">{{cite web |url= https://www.billboard.com/music/linx/chart-history/billboard-200|title=Billboard 200 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=11 July 1981 |website=Billboard.com|access-date=20 Dec 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n! [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums|US R&B Albums]]<ref name='Billboard R&B Albums'>{{cite web |url= http://www.metacritic.com/feature/now-streaming-on-netflix|title=Billboard Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=20 June 1981 |website=Metacritic.com|access-date=20 Dec 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n! Certifications\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1981\n| ''[[Intuition (album)|Intuition]]''\n| <center>8</center>\n|<center>175</center>\n|<center>39</center>\n|* [[British Phonographic Industry|BPI]]: [[Music recording certification|Silver]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bpi.co.uk/award/3374-1951-2|title=Linx: Intuition (Album)|publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry|BPI]]|website=bpi.co.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Go Ahead''\n| <center>35</center>\n|<center>-</center>\n|<center>-</center>\n|\n|}\n\n=== Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Release date\n! Title\n|[[UK Singles|UK]]<ref name=\"C\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/1526/linx/|title=Linx|publisher=[[Official Charts]]|website=officialcharts.com}}</ref>\n! [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|US R&B]]<ref name=\"Billboard R&B Charts\">{{cite web |url= https://www.billboard.com/music/linx/chart-history/r-b-hip-hop-songs|title=Hot R&B/Hip Hop Songs |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=1981 |website=Billboard.com|access-date=20 Dec 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n![[Dance Club Songs|US Dance]]<ref name=\"Billboard Dance Charts\">{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/linx/chart-history/dance-club-play-songs |title=Dance Club Charts |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=11 April 1981 |website=Billboard.com|access-date=20 Dec 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n! Certifications\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1980\n| \"Rise And Shine\"\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n|\n|-\n| \"You're Lying\"\n| <center>15</center>\n| <center>27</center>\n| <center>71</center>\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\"|1981\n| \"Intuition\"\n| <center>7</center>\n|<center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n|* [[British Phonographic Industry|BPI]]: [[Music recording certification|Silver]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bpi.co.u